This is not a hypothetical for its own sake.
It is a test of a single standard:
Do principles remain consistent—or do they shift with identity?

Now turn the lens inward.

When such crimes occur within Western societies—
with perpetrators drawn from the highest circles of wealth, power, and political influence,
with victims from within those same societies,
and with the crimes themselves unfolding at the very heart of those states—

how are they described?

They are reduced to “criminal cases.”
Carefully isolated from the systems that enabled or protected them.
Managed through language that contains the damage rather than exposing its full scope.

🔻 The inescapable conclusion

The issue is not only the crime itself,
but how it is defined, framed, and generalized:

When the perpetrator is “the other,” the crime becomes a verdict on an entire identity.
When the perpetrator is “one of us,” it becomes an individual aberration.

So what kind of moral framework is this,
that shifts with the identity of the offender?

And what credibility remains for a discourse
that cannot uphold a single standard of judgment?",2026-04-03T04:39:40Z,2,0
