The record is not opinion; it is a documented timeline. In November 1979, Iranian regime-backed students seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 66 Americans hostage for 444 days. In April 1983, an Iran‑backed group conducted a suicide bombing at the U.S. Embassy in Beirut, killing 17 Americans, and that same year a truck bomb destroyed the U.S. Marine barracks in Beirut, killing 241 U.S. service members. In 1996, the Khobar Towers bombing in Saudi Arabia, attributed to Iran‑backed operatives, killed 19 U.S. airmen, and since 2003 Iranian‑supplied explosives have been linked to the deaths of hundreds of American troops in Iraq. Even in just one recent period—from October 17, 2023 to November 19, 2024—Iran and its proxies carried out more than 180 attacks on U.S. forces in the Middle East, injuring more than 180 Americans and killing several U.S. service members. This is a continuous pattern of hostility, not an isolated grievance.
At the same time, Washington has allowed our money to be siphoned off through waste, fraud, and abuse in foreign assistance and international programs, with very little accountability to the people who actually pay the bill: American taxpayers. Reviews of U.S. foreign aid have exposed funds going to projects that either have no clear benefit to the United States or, worse, end up indirectly benefiting hostile actors, including extremists in conflict zones. The White House itself has highlighted how agencies like USAID have for decades funneled large sums into pet projects with “next‑to‑no oversight,” including instances where U.S.-funded supplies and support ended up in the hands of al‑Qaeda‑linked fighters in Syria and contributed to infrastructure that boosted Taliban-linked heroin production in Afghanistan. Congressional hearings on foreign assistance now openly focus on “waste, fraud, and abuse” and the need to protect U.S. taxpayers from exactly this sort of systemic exploitation.
All of this has taken place while America’s industrial base was hollowed out and millions of good manufacturing jobs were shipped overseas under a bipartisan consensus that treated globalization as inevitable and permanent. Between 2010 and 2019, the U.S. added about 166,000 manufacturing jobs per year on average, a slow recovery from an earlier collapse, while factories continued to close and supply chains became dangerously dependent on adversarial or unstable countries. Reshoring data show that by 2020, roughly 780,000 jobs had been brought back or created through reshoring and foreign direct investment compared with 2010, and the policy debate clearly shifted toward using tariffs, trade pressure, and industrial policy to bring production home. Under Trump, the United States leaned into this reshoring trend with aggressive tariffs and “America First” policies aimed at reducing reliance on China and reviving domestic manufacturing, even as critics argued about the pace and distribution of job growth.",2026-03-27T16:35:06Z,0,0
