Ugyj148LkEHqkqRrefl4AaABAg,9VIJnDXQZiw,https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9VIJnDXQZiw,BBC News,ilk_saldir,"President Trump's recent appeals to other nations have focused on a coalition to help keep the straight open, *NOT* asking them to join the direct military effort.

 He makes the point that all the countries he's ask will directly benefit from this request. 
 In reality, the USA really doesn't need help. *BUT*

 China, India, Japan, and South Korea receive roughly 75% to 80% of the oil and LNG that passes through the strait.  

​Iraq, Kuwait, and Qatar: These exporters are geographically trapped behind the strait. Without it, their economies lose almost all ability to export their primary resources.

​Thailand, Pakistan, and Bangladesh: These countries have thin energy reserves and are already seeing fuel shortages and surging prices.  

​Global ""Infection""
​While Europe produce more of their own energy, they are not immune. Because oil is a globally traded commodity, a shutdown would likely ​trigger a global recession, Analysts warn that losing 20% of the world's energy supply would cause a worldwide economic contraction and  
​Spike inflation, ​Disrupt Food Supplies, increase fuel and fertilizer costs, and would raise grocery prices in nearly every country on Earth.  

Not only this, but President Trump's request seems almost as if he's reinforcing the points he's made in the past, 
 He argues that European allies, through the protection of Nato, seem to have ""free-ride"" on American taxpayers 
 President Trump’s primary criticisms of NATO center on burden-sharing, the U.S. remains the largest contributor, accounting for roughly 62% of the alliance's total military spending, while other countries combined share the remainder. Keeping this in mind, the USA has the military might to cut ties with Nato and route those funds into its defense.",2026-03-17T02:09:51Z,0,0
